<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAUNA SNOW, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
'Quality' Viewers, Nielsen Disagree: A recent national survey of 3,500 members 
of a Virginia-based group seeking higher-quality TV fare greatly differed from 
the A. C. Nielsen Co. ratings. The Viewers for Quality Television Inc. survey 
respondents ranked the CBS Monday-night series "Murphy Brown" No. 1 and 
"Designing Women" as No. 2 on their most-watched list. 
</P>
<P>
Yet the latest Nielsen weeklies put those shows in a tie for 31st place. 
Further, while the Nielsens perennially place NBC's "The Cosby Show" in first 
place, the show did not even make the VQT's Top 25. The VQT members' Top 10 
were: "Murphy Brown," "Designing Women," "Roseanne," "L.A. Law," "Beauty and 
the Beast" (now canceled), "Newhart," "Cheers," "The Wonder Years," "The Golden 
Girls" and "In the Heat of the Night." SHAUNA SNOW 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
March 6, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Public Poll -- Viewers for Quality Television Inc.'s list of the 10 
most-watched TV shows in Monday's Morning Report was compiled from a poll of 
800 members of the public who had written to the organization. Wire reports 
incorrectly attributed the list to the Virginia-based group's 3,500 members. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
