<P>
Channel One Debuts: Channel One, a news show with advertisements aimed at 
teen-agers, debuts today in 400 schools across the country amid an uproar over 
whether the two minutes of commercials included in each 12-minute show corrupts 
the school day. 
</P>
<P>
Several national education groups are opposing Channel One and officials in 
California and New York have prohibited public schools in those states from 
carrying the program. In addition, North Carolina has asked a state court to 
enforce its board of education's ban on the program. Channel One maintains that 
the commercials are essential because the $150,000 charge for each 30-second 
commercial pays for the $150 million in video equipment loaned to schools that 
show the program. SHAUNA SNOW 
</P>
