<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICAN CONTINENTAL ALTERED LINCOLN DATA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHOENIX 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American Continental Corp. officials prepared for the first major federal 
examination of Irvine, Calif.-based Lincoln Savings and Loan in 1986 by 
rewriting thousands of pages of corporate documents and falsifying directors' 
signatures, a newspaper reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Phoenix-based American Continental, run by financier Charles 
H. Keating Jr., destroyed the original documents, according to the Arizona 
Republic. 
</P>
<P>
Investigators have long alleged that forgery and back-dating of files and 
documents were common throughout much of American Continental's ownership of 
Lincoln Savings. 
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it obtained copies of Lincoln's board of directors' minutes 
and resolutions dated from Feb. 22, 1984, when Keating bought Lincoln, through 
Dec. 30, 1985. The newspaper hired James Hale, a certified questioned-documents 
examiner, to examine the signatures on the documents. 
</P>
<P>
Hale concluded that 1,080 of 1,822 signatures were falsified. He said that all 
of the signatures on 235 of 432 of the documents were falsified and that only 
78 documents contained all authentic signatures, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that a former attorney for Lincoln Savings and Loan, Mark 
Sauter, and a former American Continental paralegal, Sherry Blixt Smith, 
admitted that the documents were rewritten and the signatures faked, but they 
called the changes technical. They said the alterations were neither 
significant nor deceitful. 
</P>
<P>
American Continental filed for protection from creditors in Bankruptcy Court in 
April 1989. The government subsequently took control of Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
Keating is the target of federal and congressional probes and on Friday was 
named in accusations by California state authorities. 
</P>
<P>
Employees said the documents were rewritten during an effort before the start 
of a seven-month-long examination of the thrift's books by the San Francisco 
office of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board in March 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
