<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: MARKET WATCH; 
</P>
<P>
BEING SLICKER THAN TEFLON AT AMERICAN EXPRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
James D. Robinson III has a set of moves that even the late Harry Houdini, the 
leading escape artist of his time, would have admired. The difference is that 
Houdini escaped from tanks filled with water, and Robinson, chairman of 
American Express Co., escapes from tanks filled with sharks. Corporate sharks, 
that is. 
</P>
<P>
It is really slick. Within the past year, Robinson has walked away, seemingly 
untouched, from at least four debacles that would have gotten most corporate 
chairmen torn apart. The list: 
</P>
<P>
* The disaster at Shearson Lehman Hutton, in which American Express finally 
said Sunday that it would buy up the 39% of the stock in the brokerage that it 
doesn't already own by exchanging 0.426 of its own shares for each Shearson 
share. 
</P>
<P>
* The Safra scandal, in which American Express was caught falsely accusing 
banker Edmund Safra, one of its competitors, of laundering money, and ended up 
agreeing to pay $8 million to Safra-selected charities to buy its way out of 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
* The insider trading scandal, in which American Express' investment banker, 
Salim B. (Sandy) Lewis, pleaded guilty to manipulating the price of Fireman's 
Fund stock upward on American Express' behalf. There's no sign that AmEx knew 
or condoned what Lewis has pleaded guilty to doing, but it raises the question 
of how American Express came to have a crook representing it. 
</P>
<P>
* The RJR Nabisco fiasco, described in the best-selling book "Barbarians at the 
Gate." The authors describe in great detail the behind-the-scenes role that 
Robinson, unhappy with the way Shearson Chairman Peter A. Cohen was handling 
things, played in trying to help Shearson do the deal. Cohen has taken the 
blame, but you have to wonder why Shearson fared so miserably despite so much 
personal attention from Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
In most big, visible companies such as AmEx, any of these four reverses would 
have led to reams of news articles wondering who should be blamed. Any two 
within a year would have sparked a spate of "What's Going On at American 
Express?" articles. All four would have put the chairman on the street. 
</P>
<P>
Yet, here is Jim Robinson, sailing along, seemingly unscathed. Likewise, 
American Express maintains its reputation as a well-managed, high-class 
company. This has to be one of the best jobs of financial public relations in 
the memory of man. It's such a good campaign that you don't even see it. 
</P>
<P>
Consider the Shearson debacle. AmEx, which paid $900 million for Shearson in 
1981 and up until Sunday's announcement owned 61% of it, had been offering 
Shearson around for months. Last week American Express said if it couldn't find 
a buyer it was going to put $1 billion into Shearson just to save it. As the 
late Sen. Everett Dirksen once said, "A billion dollars here and a billion 
dollars there, and soon you're talking about real money." 
</P>
<P>
Robinson, of course, wasn't running Shearson. But he had AmEx buy the company, 
he presided over the departure of Shearson Chairman Sanford I. (Sandy) Weill 
and he installed Cohen, on whose watch disaster has struck. 
</P>
<P>
How does Robinson escape all this unscathed? 
</P>
<P>
Part of the answer, of course, is that except for Shearson, none of these 
things makes a significant difference in American Express' income statement. 
</P>
<P>
As American Express' first-rate public relations people point out, shareholders 
have done quite well under Robinson. American Express' stock is up 367% in the 
10 years ending Dec. 31, 1989, compared to 228% for the Dow Jones industrials 
and 227% for the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index. American Express makes 
good money; its balance sheet is strong; it has made some fine acquisitions 
such as Investors Diversified Services. 
</P>
<P>
You can argue that American Express would have done even better had it stuck to 
its franchises rather than embarking on a series of glitzy, largely 
undistinguished diversifications that distracted money and management effort 
from credit cards, direct marketing and Travel Related Services. But that's an 
abstract argument, hard for stockholders to get excited about. 
</P>
<P>
The real secret to Robinson's ability to escape being tarred with disasters is 
probably that he is extremely adept at what PR people call "damage control." 
This often seems to consist of throwing people over the side, quickly. These 
human sacrifices seem to appease the gods. It's the decentralized, "my 
responsibility, your fault" school of management. 
</P>
<P>
This has been the pattern since at least 1979, when American Express launched a 
hostile takeover attempt for McGraw-Hill, the publisher of Business Week 
magazine, then backed off for reasons that have never been disclosed. The human 
sacrifice in that case was American Express President Roger Morley, who also 
served on the board of McGraw-Hill. He's now known in some quarters as 
"Morley's ghost." 
</P>
<P>
Peter Cohen served as the human sacrifice for both the Shearson and RJR Nabisco 
reverses. And Harry Freeman, an executive vice president in the corporate 
affairs department, took early retirement for failing to detect and stop the 
smear campaign against Safra. Sandy Lewis, of course, was the fall guy for the 
Fireman's Fund manipulation, which took place years ago but for which Lewis 
pleaded guilty last year. 
</P>
<P>
In all, an amazing escape record. If Robinson can ever distill and manufacture 
whatever it is that allows him to be so good at deflecting criticism, American 
Express will have a fabulous new product. One that will put Teflon to shame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, James D. Robinson III Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
